1
00:00:02,068 --> 00:00:03,467
The trick to onions...

2
00:00:03,500 --> 00:00:04,734
cut them in half lengthwise,

3
00:00:04,767 --> 00:00:07,101
but leave the roots on.

4
00:00:07,134 --> 00:00:09,467
Then make your vertical slices.

5
00:00:12,667 --> 00:00:14,333
Need a dozen. Think you can handle this?

6
00:00:14,400 --> 00:00:16,801
A dozen is 12, right?

7
00:00:16,867 --> 00:00:19,434
Next, we add mustard greens...

8
00:00:19,500 --> 00:00:22,367
spicy, and they pack a nice punch.

9
00:00:22,434 --> 00:00:24,634
Plus, they're really good for you.

10
00:00:24,701 --> 00:00:26,567
Improve mental function,

11
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:28,600
protect against rheumatoid arthritis.

12
00:00:28,634 --> 00:00:31,801
Even inhibit certain types of cancer.

13
00:00:31,867 --> 00:00:33,001
Are you going to chop those onions

14
00:00:33,068 --> 00:00:34,567
or give them a thai massage?

15
00:00:34,600 --> 00:00:37,867
Well, i guess a happy ending|is out of the question.

16
00:00:37,901 --> 00:00:39,734
I don't recall adding|making snide remarks

17
00:00:39,801 --> 00:00:42,767
to your list of duties.

18
00:00:42,801 --> 00:00:44,300
Just taking initiative.

19
00:00:44,333 --> 00:00:47,567
Secret ingredient: porcini mushrooms.

20
00:00:47,600 --> 00:00:50,333
You want to reconstitute|them in a bowl of water.

21
00:00:50,400 --> 00:00:52,600
You also want to hire an assistant

22
00:00:52,634 --> 00:00:54,467
who can stay focused for|longer than 30 seconds.

23
00:00:54,534 --> 00:00:55,867
Why don't i hear you chopping?

24
00:00:55,901 --> 00:00:57,834
Just give me a second.

25
00:00:57,901 --> 00:01:00,233
You're kidding me, right?

26
00:01:00,267 --> 00:01:02,634
So sorry. Are you okay?|You want to sit down?

27
00:01:02,701 --> 00:01:04,867
My lips are blue. Cyanosis.

28
00:01:04,901 --> 00:01:07,333
Pain in my back and chest.

29
00:01:07,367 --> 00:01:09,267
Spontaneous pneumothorax.

30
00:01:09,333 --> 00:01:11,233
What are you talking|about? I'm a doctor.

31
00:01:11,267 --> 00:01:13,034
You are? And i need a doctor.

32
00:02:02,400 --> 00:02:03,834
You drool.

33
00:02:03,901 --> 00:02:06,667
Shut up.

34
00:03:03,500 --> 00:03:05,500
I know gas is expensive,

35
00:03:05,534 --> 00:03:07,333
but i could've given you a ride.

36
00:03:08,867 --> 00:03:09,901
Elevator's broken.

37
00:03:09,967 --> 00:03:11,234
It was fine when i came up

38
00:03:11,300 --> 00:03:12,867
from admitting.

39
00:03:12,934 --> 00:03:14,333
Dana miller, the cancer researcher.

40
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:17,500
Spontaneous pneumothorax.|Awfully thin file.

41
00:03:17,567 --> 00:03:19,101
She just got admitted.

42
00:03:19,134 --> 00:03:20,867
Lots of things can cause pneumothorax.

43
00:03:20,934 --> 00:03:22,433
Why don't we let eight|or ten other doctors

44
00:03:22,500 --> 00:03:23,467
rule out the boring stuff?

45
00:03:23,500 --> 00:03:24,767
We wanna take this case.

46
00:03:24,834 --> 00:03:26,433
She's maybe five or ten years away

47
00:03:26,500 --> 00:03:27,867
from curing retinoblastoma.

48
00:03:27,934 --> 00:03:30,500
Which would make this|case attractive to anyone

49
00:03:30,567 --> 00:03:33,600
who has some vested interest|in people curing the incurable.

50
00:03:33,667 --> 00:03:34,433
She hasn't suffered from copd.

51
00:03:34,500 --> 00:03:35,767
She doesn't smoke.

52
00:03:35,834 --> 00:03:37,634
She hasn't been scuba diving.

53
00:03:37,700 --> 00:03:39,500
O2 sats are low even|after chest tube insertion.

54
00:03:39,534 --> 00:03:41,801
Pneumothorax could be|secondary to a bunch of things.

55
00:03:41,867 --> 00:03:43,433
Cystic fibrosis, lung cancer.

56
00:03:43,500 --> 00:03:46,034
Or, to be slightly more optimistic,

57
00:03:46,067 --> 00:03:48,333
late-onset asthma triggered|by an unknown allergen.

58
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:50,001
We have a case? Did|you just get to work?

59
00:03:50,067 --> 00:03:51,400
Am i in trouble?

60
00:03:51,433 --> 00:03:54,801
Did you take the elevators up? Yes.

61
00:03:54,867 --> 00:03:57,034
So, steroids for asthma?

62
00:03:57,067 --> 00:03:58,934
Yeah.

63
00:03:58,967 --> 00:04:02,400
Do a ct looking for|hyperinflation to confirm.

64
00:04:07,433 --> 00:04:10,134
I thought my hospital was high-tech.

65
00:04:10,168 --> 00:04:11,901
I'd have to wait all day for a ct.

66
00:04:11,967 --> 00:04:13,801
Dr. House gets a few perks.

67
00:04:13,834 --> 00:04:15,500
He has his own scanner?

68
00:04:15,534 --> 00:04:18,034
No, just very loose interpretations

69
00:04:18,101 --> 00:04:19,400
of hospital procedure.

70
00:04:19,467 --> 00:04:21,400
I appreciate the extra effort, but...

71
00:04:21,433 --> 00:04:22,801
our gift to society.

72
00:04:22,867 --> 00:04:24,634
We want to get you back to|work as soon as possible.

73
00:04:24,700 --> 00:04:27,001
Well, i'm not working.

74
00:04:27,067 --> 00:04:28,934
At least not as a doctor.

75
00:04:29,001 --> 00:04:30,734
I quit.

76
00:04:30,401 --> 00:04:33,634
I left eight months ago.

77
00:04:33,667 --> 00:04:35,601
You mean, like, a sabbatical?

78
00:04:35,667 --> 00:04:38,467
I had a uterine myoma. Benign.

79
00:04:38,501 --> 00:04:42,067
But it ruptured and i|needed emergency surgery.

80
00:04:42,134 --> 00:04:43,701
I was lying there on the table thinking,

81
00:04:43,768 --> 00:04:45,868
"i can't die now. I|haven't been happy yet."

82
00:04:45,900 --> 00:04:49,734
Couldn't you just buy an|overpriced german sports car,

83
00:04:49,801 --> 00:04:51,334
or have an affair?

84
00:04:51,401 --> 00:04:55,167
My sports car is doing|what i want when i want.

85
00:04:55,234 --> 00:04:56,701
Right now i'm learning|how to run a kitchen

86
00:04:56,768 --> 00:04:58,067
from one of the best chefs in new york.

87
00:04:58,134 --> 00:05:01,567
You're washing pots and smashing garlic?

88
00:05:01,601 --> 00:05:03,768
Smashing garlic makes me happy.

89
00:05:03,801 --> 00:05:05,868
Before that it was eight years studying,

90
00:05:05,933 --> 00:05:07,234
12 years in that lab.

91
00:05:07,300 --> 00:05:09,200
It was always what i was supposed to do,

92
00:05:09,234 --> 00:05:10,701
and never what i wanted to do.

93
00:05:22,900 --> 00:05:24,334
Come here. Look at this.

94
00:05:24,367 --> 00:05:26,634
Come here.

95
00:05:30,701 --> 00:05:33,768
Adorable. Elevators keep crashing.

96
00:05:33,801 --> 00:05:35,868
Is mercury in retrograde or what?

97
00:05:35,900 --> 00:05:37,567
Elevators can be capricious.

98
00:05:37,634 --> 00:05:40,768
Sometimes it just seems|like they're out to get you.

99
00:05:40,801 --> 00:05:42,134
She keeps playing with the blanket.

100
00:05:42,167 --> 00:05:43,234
Why would she do that?

101
00:05:43,267 --> 00:05:45,334
Why do you think the elevators

102
00:05:45,401 --> 00:05:46,868
would be out to get me?

103
00:05:46,900 --> 00:05:48,300
I don't know.

104
00:05:48,334 --> 00:05:50,868
Maybe they wanted to take time off

105
00:05:50,933 --> 00:05:52,667
to spend with their little dumbwaiter.

106
00:05:52,734 --> 00:05:54,967
But they the had to leave it|at home with an elevator sitter

107
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:56,900
because you drove the|replacement elevator

108
00:05:56,967 --> 00:05:59,167
to quitting

109
00:05:59,200 --> 00:06:01,667
because you're incapable of|listening to anybody but me.

110
00:06:01,734 --> 00:06:03,467
That's just a theory.

111
00:06:03,534 --> 00:06:05,933
You're wrong. I don't|even listen to you.

112
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:08,667
Either do your job or go|home. Leave me out of it.

113
00:06:08,734 --> 00:06:09,967
I am gonna do my job.

114
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:11,534
It doesn't mean i have to do it happily.

115
00:06:11,601 --> 00:06:13,734
Doesn't mean i have to|do it without resentment.

116
00:06:13,801 --> 00:06:15,434
And it definitely doesn't|mean i have to do it

117
00:06:15,501 --> 00:06:18,200
without seeking vengeance on|the person making me be here.

118
00:06:18,267 --> 00:06:19,900
Congratulations.

119
00:06:19,967 --> 00:06:22,033
You've officially dragged|me down to your level.

120
00:06:24,167 --> 00:06:25,200
Okay.

121
00:06:49,734 --> 00:06:50,868
Hey, blue.

122
00:06:58,467 --> 00:06:59,667
It's not asthma.

123
00:06:59,734 --> 00:07:01,601
Lung volume is normal.

124
00:07:01,667 --> 00:07:04,334
She did have a uterine myoma|removed eight months ago.

125
00:07:04,401 --> 00:07:06,900
Central line iv could have|made a hole near the lung

126
00:07:06,933 --> 00:07:08,567
that slowly expanded.

127
00:07:08,634 --> 00:07:09,834
No pleural thickening.

128
00:07:09,900 --> 00:07:12,000
I can't believe she quit.

129
00:07:12,033 --> 00:07:15,167
People have the right to be happy.

130
00:07:15,200 --> 00:07:16,534
I saw a four-year-old|with retinoblastoma

131
00:07:16,567 --> 00:07:18,634
on my oncology rotation.

132
00:07:18,667 --> 00:07:21,467
The cancer had eaten through|her eye and into her brain.

133
00:07:21,534 --> 00:07:22,801
Horrible diseases exist.

134
00:07:22,834 --> 00:07:24,267
It doesn't mean people should give up

135
00:07:24,300 --> 00:07:25,768
recreational anything.

136
00:07:25,834 --> 00:07:27,234
Why not? Big picture...

137
00:07:27,300 --> 00:07:28,701
i don't care if jonas salk's life

138
00:07:28,734 --> 00:07:29,967
is a miserable shell.

139
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:31,567
I just want him to cure polio.

140
00:07:31,601 --> 00:07:33,434
You can't live your life "big picture."

141
00:07:33,501 --> 00:07:34,567
You've gotta look out for yourself

142
00:07:34,601 --> 00:07:35,701
and the people you care about.

143
00:07:35,768 --> 00:07:37,534
Well, then, why are you a doctor?

144
00:07:37,601 --> 00:07:38,534
Why aren't you sitting by a pool in fiji

145
00:07:38,601 --> 00:07:40,000
knocking back mai tais?

146
00:07:40,033 --> 00:07:41,734
People act in their own self-interests.

147
00:07:41,768 --> 00:07:43,933
You're all here because|you're happy to be here.

148
00:07:43,967 --> 00:07:45,534
Or at least because|it's your best option.

149
00:07:45,601 --> 00:07:46,634
I'm here because i want to help people.

150
00:07:46,667 --> 00:07:48,801
No, you're here because

151
00:07:48,868 --> 00:07:51,167
it makes you feel good to help people.

152
00:07:51,234 --> 00:07:52,567
Taub and foreman are here because

153
00:07:52,601 --> 00:07:54,234
they've got no other viable choices.

154
00:07:54,300 --> 00:07:55,701
And thirteen is desperate|to make her life matter

155
00:07:55,768 --> 00:07:58,367
before it's over.

156
00:07:58,401 --> 00:08:00,434
So... you're happy to be here?

157
00:08:00,501 --> 00:08:01,801
Does it show?

158
00:08:01,834 --> 00:08:06,701
Are those... increased|interstitial markings?

159
00:08:06,768 --> 00:08:08,501
Could be pulmonary fibrosis.

160
00:08:08,534 --> 00:08:10,401
Do a biopsy.

161
00:08:12,167 --> 00:08:13,967
Foreman.

162
00:08:14,033 --> 00:08:20,367
"You've got to look out for|the people you care about."

163
00:08:20,434 --> 00:08:21,868
That wouldn't have|anything to do with you

164
00:08:21,933 --> 00:08:23,768
screwing over your clinical trial

165
00:08:23,834 --> 00:08:25,900
by slipping thirteen|the real drug, would it?

166
00:08:25,967 --> 00:08:28,734
You said that would be stupid.

167
00:08:28,768 --> 00:08:30,601
Does she know?

168
00:08:30,667 --> 00:08:32,734
Because jonas salk would not approve.

169
00:08:32,768 --> 00:08:35,567
There's nothing to know.

170
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,601
Got it?

171
00:08:47,434 --> 00:08:49,000
Good? Yep.

172
00:08:49,067 --> 00:08:51,267
You okay?

173
00:08:51,334 --> 00:08:54,000
Just a headache. I took|some ibuprofen, but...

174
00:08:54,067 --> 00:08:54,967
where's the pain: front or back?

175
00:08:55,033 --> 00:08:56,234
Front.

176
00:08:56,267 --> 00:08:57,501
Why are there never|any interesting pictures

177
00:08:57,534 --> 00:08:58,834
on these cards?

178
00:08:58,868 --> 00:09:00,868
They should make a dirty version.

179
00:09:00,900 --> 00:09:02,967
A sharp pain, or more of a throbbing...

180
00:09:03,033 --> 00:09:06,967
relax, it's not a side|effect. People get headaches.

181
00:09:07,033 --> 00:09:09,467
True, but i can get you an mri.

182
00:09:09,501 --> 00:09:11,567
If i'm on the drug, it's been weeks.

183
00:09:11,634 --> 00:09:14,601
It's not like something's|going to suddenly crop up now.

184
00:09:14,634 --> 00:09:17,367
Okay.

185
00:09:17,434 --> 00:09:20,100
First card.

186
00:09:20,167 --> 00:09:24,000
Train, duck...

187
00:09:24,067 --> 00:09:25,401
you can't remember?

188
00:09:25,434 --> 00:09:27,734
Piano.

189
00:09:30,067 --> 00:09:31,933
We need a biopsy to confirm...

190
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:35,134
you need an open-lung biopsy|to confirm pulmonary fibrosis.

191
00:09:35,167 --> 00:09:37,234
That's invasive surgery.

192
00:09:37,267 --> 00:09:38,933
I'd be out of commission for weeks.

193
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,601
No offense, but you're not working.

194
00:09:41,634 --> 00:09:43,334
What does it matter if you|spend a little time in bed?

195
00:09:43,401 --> 00:09:45,534
Not working doesn't mean|i don't have places to go.

196
00:09:45,567 --> 00:09:48,334
I've got my book group, piano|lessons, cooking classes.

197
00:09:48,367 --> 00:09:49,801
They make me happy.

198
00:09:49,834 --> 00:09:51,768
A warm apple fritter makes me happy.

199
00:09:51,834 --> 00:09:53,834
It doesn't fulfill me as a person.

200
00:09:53,900 --> 00:09:55,134
And working here does?

201
00:09:55,200 --> 00:09:56,234
If it didn't, i'd have found a way

202
00:09:56,267 --> 00:09:57,000
to go back to tucking tummies.

203
00:09:57,067 --> 00:09:58,434
Well, good for you.

204
00:09:58,467 --> 00:10:01,134
If your job fulfills you and|makes you happy, that's rare.

205
00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:04,267
I didn't say i was happy.

206
00:10:04,334 --> 00:10:06,367
I loved being a plastic surgeon.

207
00:10:06,434 --> 00:10:09,000
The money, the lifestyle.

208
00:10:09,067 --> 00:10:11,167
And in a lot of ways this job stinks.

209
00:10:11,200 --> 00:10:15,467
I'm making five bucks, i'm|always annoyed... but...

210
00:10:15,534 --> 00:10:17,868
you can look yourself|in the mirror and think,

211
00:10:17,933 --> 00:10:19,900
"i did something worthwhile today."

212
00:10:19,933 --> 00:10:22,401
Exactly.

213
00:10:22,467 --> 00:10:25,601
Well, that's important.|And i do miss that.

214
00:10:25,667 --> 00:10:29,200
But it just wasn't enough anymore.

215
00:10:34,900 --> 00:10:36,601
That doesn't feel right.

216
00:10:36,667 --> 00:10:37,933
Sit up.

217
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:40,267
Ow! Oh, that's weird.

218
00:10:43,467 --> 00:10:45,100
What is it? Ascites?

219
00:10:56,534 --> 00:10:58,834
First her lung deflates,|like me after a cold shower.

220
00:11:00,001 --> 00:11:02,934
Now her liver starts to|bleed, like me after...

221
00:11:08,300 --> 00:11:09,467
you okay?

222
00:11:09,500 --> 00:11:11,001
Great.

223
00:11:11,068 --> 00:11:15,567
Just practicing my|clown college audition.

224
00:11:15,600 --> 00:11:18,667
Someone set a trip wire.

225
00:11:18,701 --> 00:11:20,400
We were with the patient the whole time.

226
00:11:20,434 --> 00:11:22,001
We were in the grc.

227
00:11:22,068 --> 00:11:24,367
Lung, liver, go.

228
00:11:24,400 --> 00:11:26,233
Shouldn't you be obsessing|over who did this to you?

229
00:11:26,300 --> 00:11:27,567
Nope... anybody bother

230
00:11:27,600 --> 00:11:29,267
mriing our patient's liver for tumors?

231
00:11:29,333 --> 00:11:32,567
Uh, no tumors, no|cysts, no clear etiology.

232
00:11:32,600 --> 00:11:35,867
If you're not obsessing,

233
00:11:35,934 --> 00:11:38,500
you must have already figured it out.

234
00:11:38,567 --> 00:11:39,901
Yes.

235
00:11:39,967 --> 00:11:41,333
So i'm obsessing about|why you're not obsessing

236
00:11:41,367 --> 00:11:43,567
about why our patient's|liver suddenly sprang a leak.

237
00:11:43,634 --> 00:11:46,101
There's a tiny spot on the caudate lobe.

238
00:11:46,168 --> 00:11:47,467
Could be a granuloma.

239
00:11:47,534 --> 00:11:49,500
Erodes into the hepatic artery,

240
00:11:49,534 --> 00:11:50,901
causes the bleed.

241
00:11:50,967 --> 00:11:52,434
What caused the granuloma?

242
00:11:52,500 --> 00:11:54,701
Blastomycosis.

243
00:11:54,767 --> 00:11:56,200
Could have been asymptomatic for months.

244
00:11:56,233 --> 00:11:59,034
It hits her lungs, we give her steroids.

245
00:11:59,068 --> 00:12:01,200
It blossoms and attacks her liver.

246
00:12:01,233 --> 00:12:03,567
Get a piece of her lung,|stick it under a black light.

247
00:12:03,600 --> 00:12:06,967
If it glows, sick children|who need her souffles

248
00:12:07,034 --> 00:12:08,634
can breathe easier.

249
00:12:08,701 --> 00:12:10,667
Foreman.

250
00:12:14,967 --> 00:12:16,467
Again?

251
00:12:16,534 --> 00:12:18,200
You have a problem.

252
00:12:18,267 --> 00:12:19,333
I told you, i didn't...

253
00:12:19,367 --> 00:12:21,600
then you really have a problem.

254
00:12:21,634 --> 00:12:24,367
They way she turned her|head to look at the mri...

255
00:12:24,434 --> 00:12:25,834
i think she's losing|her peripheral vision.

256
00:12:25,901 --> 00:12:28,400
Because she turned her head?

257
00:12:28,434 --> 00:12:30,701
I'm happy for you.

258
00:12:30,734 --> 00:12:33,567
A love so deep you're ready|to chuck your medical license

259
00:12:33,634 --> 00:12:35,101
to give her powerful, unproven drugs

260
00:12:35,168 --> 00:12:37,801
with dangerous side effects.

261
00:12:37,867 --> 00:12:39,001
I don't want to make any assumptions

262
00:12:39,068 --> 00:12:40,367
about your feelings for me,

263
00:12:40,434 --> 00:12:42,634
but i do have a birthday coming up.

264
00:12:53,367 --> 00:12:58,267
I hear cuddy's seal training|finally came in handy.

265
00:12:58,333 --> 00:13:00,567
Should i be investing in a flak jacket?

266
00:13:00,634 --> 00:13:01,901
You're safe.

267
00:13:01,934 --> 00:13:04,467
No carpet bombing?

268
00:13:04,534 --> 00:13:08,634
No burning of dresden|to teach her a lesson?

269
00:13:08,701 --> 00:13:10,734
